Solanaceae
, an angiosperm family of ~2500 species and 100 genera, include some of the world’ s most economically valuable and historically important crops such as potatoes, tobacco, tomatoes, eggplants, and peppers (

). The family is a source of pharmaceutical compounds and model organisms (e.g., tobacco, tomato, and petunia) and is known for its diverse reproductive structures (


– 


). One well-studied feature found in several 
Solanaceae
genera is the inflated calyx syndrome (ICS), in which complex signaling pathways cause the calyx to expand after fertilization and surround the fruit (

, 

), as in tomatillos and other lantern fruits.

Despite increasing interest in the timing and biogeography of 
Solanaceae
evolution (

), the family’ s poor fossil record provides little information. There are no valid previous records of fossil flowers, fruits, or leaves of 
Solanaceae
(

). Several Eocene-Pliocene isolated seeds are known, but except for some Oligocene and younger specimens assigned to the large 
Solanoideae
clade, they cannot be placed in derived groups (

). Molecular divergence estimates for the crown group of the family range from ~3 5 to 5 1 million years ago (Ma) (

) and, most recently, ~30 Ma, based on intensive taxon sampling and critical use of the available fossils for temporal calibrations (

). Recent estimates of the 
Solanaceae
divergence from 
Convolvulaceae
vary from ~49 to 67 Ma (

, 

, 

). The 
Solanaceae
are thought to have evolved and diversified on late- or post-Gondwanan South America (

, 

), which is the family’ s center of diversity today (

). Nevertheless, Miocene wood from Argentina (

) has been the only physical evidence of its South American history.

We discovered these fossils at Laguna del Hunco in Chubut, Patagonia, Argentina, an early Eocene caldera-lake, fossil rainforest locality that represents the terminal phase of Gondwana and the global warmth of the early Eocene climatic optimum (

, 

). The assemblage is dominated by Gondwanic taxa with fossil and extant Austral- asian affinities (


– 


). There are few reliable previous records from the site of characteristically New World taxa, suggesting minimal linkage of late-Gondwanan and extant South American floras due to cooling and regional extinctions since the late Eocene (

). The minimum age of the fossils is 52.22 ± 0.22 Ma, based on three 40Ar-39Ar dates from closely associated tuffs and two paleomagnetic reversals from the local stratigraphic section (

, 
20
).

Inflated, five-angled calyces and other features of fruiting 

Physalis

help make it one of the most recognizable angiosperm genera, although calyx expansion, by itself, is plesiomorphic within the family (

, 

, 

). However, several more detailed characters of 
Solanaceae
fruiting calyces are noted for their systematic value (

, 


– 


). To assess the phylogenetic position of the fossils, we scored a 16-character morphological matrix (table S 

